00:00:24.180 --> 00:00:30.930
So, we continue our discussion
of quantum states of light,

00:00:30.930 --> 00:00:36.360
and we focus on single
photons as qubits today.

00:00:36.360 --> 00:00:40.600
But before I get
into this, I want

00:00:40.600 --> 00:00:44.520
to ask you if you have any
questions about the last unit

00:00:44.520 --> 00:00:49.190
we be completed on Wednesday--
namely, the discussion or non

00:00:49.190 --> 00:00:52.950
classical light-- in
particular, squeezing light--

00:00:52.950 --> 00:00:58.090
and we also discussed a lot
of exciting quantum mechanical

00:00:58.090 --> 00:01:01.520
effects related
to beam splitters.

00:01:01.520 --> 00:01:03.350
So, any questions?

00:01:03.350 --> 00:01:06.290
Anything you would
like to see discussed?

00:01:14.050 --> 00:01:20.160
So, as I pointed out,
we want to now talk

00:01:20.160 --> 00:01:25.240
about realization of quantum
logic and quantum gates

00:01:25.240 --> 00:01:28.170
with single photons, but I
also said that we are actually

00:01:28.170 --> 00:01:31.155
using the language of
quantum communications--

00:01:31.155 --> 00:01:34.060
a kind of information
processing to describe

00:01:34.060 --> 00:01:37.970
general physics in
a very nice way.

00:01:37.970 --> 00:01:41.360
So, first-- when we
talk about photons,

00:01:41.360 --> 00:01:50.500
we should talk about our
qubits, and right now, you

00:01:50.500 --> 00:01:53.410
may think that having
a single photon

00:01:53.410 --> 00:01:56.910
and having no photon in a
mode are two possibilities.

00:01:56.910 --> 00:01:59.430
And you could use
them as qubits.

00:01:59.430 --> 00:02:03.160
However, I will tell you today
that it is better, actually,

00:02:03.160 --> 00:02:07.340
to use always one photon, but in
two different wave guides-- two

00:02:07.340 --> 00:02:10.050
different modes.

00:02:10.050 --> 00:02:13.220
But, we'll get
there in a moment.

00:02:13.220 --> 00:02:20.410
So, the first task at hand is
we want to manipulate photons.

00:02:20.410 --> 00:02:24.390
And for that, I want to
introduce phase shifters

00:02:24.390 --> 00:02:26.170
and beam splitters.

00:02:26.170 --> 00:02:28.990
And just to give you the
punchline right away,

00:02:28.990 --> 00:02:32.750
what I want to show you is that
those two simple devices --

00:02:32.750 --> 00:02:36.796
beam splitter, a half-silvered
mirror, a phase shifter,

00:02:36.796 --> 00:02:39.170
which is just a piece of glass
which you can put into one

00:02:39.170 --> 00:02:44.340
of the laser beams-- that those
two elements and those two

00:02:44.340 --> 00:02:50.420
basic operations, if they
are now put together--

00:02:50.420 --> 00:02:52.760
if you do a beam
splitter, a phase shifter,

00:02:52.760 --> 00:02:56.490
another beam splitter and such--
you can realize any single

00:02:56.490 --> 00:02:58.300
qubit operation.

00:02:58.300 --> 00:03:02.250
Therefore, if you have
our qubit cubic state

00:03:02.250 --> 00:03:08.150
with single photons, any
possible state of those qubit

00:03:08.150 --> 00:03:11.140
can be realized using
these optical elements.

00:03:11.140 --> 00:03:14.670
Therefore, when I say we want
to realize how we can manipulate

00:03:14.670 --> 00:03:16.570
photons with optical
elements and such,

00:03:16.570 --> 00:03:19.390
I'm not going for a zoo
of optical elements.

00:03:19.390 --> 00:03:23.430
Those two will do it all.

00:03:23.430 --> 00:03:27.520
So, with the phase
shifter, that's

00:03:27.520 --> 00:03:30.020
what we discussed at
the end of last class.

00:03:30.020 --> 00:03:36.210
If you have two modes, and
we shift the phase in one

00:03:36.210 --> 00:03:39.930
of the modes, just simply
put a piece of glass into it,

00:03:39.930 --> 00:03:41.630
then there is a phase shift.

00:03:41.630 --> 00:03:44.220
And why do we need two modes?

00:03:44.220 --> 00:03:47.070
Well, phases are
usually-- at least

00:03:47.070 --> 00:03:49.010
in experiments-- not
absolutely defined.

00:03:49.010 --> 00:03:52.020
You need a phase
reference, and here,

00:03:52.020 --> 00:03:56.520
the mode a acts as
a phase reference.

00:03:56.520 --> 00:03:59.830
Let me address one question
which a student asked me

00:03:59.830 --> 00:04:02.950
after class, and
this was related

00:04:02.950 --> 00:04:09.680
to what phases appear
in more than one place.

00:04:09.680 --> 00:04:12.060
The student's
question was motivated

00:04:12.060 --> 00:04:15.290
that if you have one
photon, it's a flux state.

00:04:15.290 --> 00:04:18.360
A flux state is a circle
in the causal probability,

00:04:18.360 --> 00:04:21.450
and therefore, the electric
field has no phase.

00:04:21.450 --> 00:04:24.560
Well, this is the phase
of the electric field,

00:04:24.560 --> 00:04:28.780
but here, we're talking about
the phase of the wave function.

00:04:28.780 --> 00:04:32.050
And a flux state within
photons is an eigenstate

00:04:32.050 --> 00:04:33.630
of the harmonic oscillator.

00:04:33.630 --> 00:04:36.780
It has a time dependence,
e to the i omega t,

00:04:36.780 --> 00:04:38.660
and we can change its phase.

00:04:38.660 --> 00:04:41.950
So, this is a kind of phase
shift I've introduced here.

00:04:49.110 --> 00:04:55.810
So, the second element
we need to realize--

00:04:55.810 --> 00:04:59.490
arbitrary single qubit
operation is the beam splitter,

00:04:59.490 --> 00:05:03.600
and I introduced a beam splitter
by just saying, hey look,

00:05:03.600 --> 00:05:05.460
I think that's a
good Hamiltonian.

00:05:05.460 --> 00:05:08.300
Let's see what this Hamiltonian
does to the two modes,

00:05:08.300 --> 00:05:11.550
and then we realize-- yes,
it takes those two modes,

00:05:11.550 --> 00:05:15.710
and it mixes the modes with
cosine theta sine theta reading

00:05:15.710 --> 00:05:16.500
factors.

00:05:16.500 --> 00:05:20.390
That's exactly what you
expect a beam splitter to do.

00:05:20.390 --> 00:05:22.570
I'm not sure we need
here now because it's

00:05:22.570 --> 00:05:24.380
part of your
homework assignment.

00:05:24.380 --> 00:05:28.310
You will show that if you
have a coherent state,

00:05:28.310 --> 00:05:32.430
the coherent state is
split by a ratio which

00:05:32.430 --> 00:05:35.280
is cosine square theta
sine square theta.

00:05:35.280 --> 00:05:38.270
So, it's exactly what you'd
expect from a beam splitter.

00:05:38.270 --> 00:05:40.510
So from that, you
realize now what

00:05:40.510 --> 00:05:44.860
this angle theta is, which I
just put into the Hamiltonian.

00:05:44.860 --> 00:05:47.260
The cosine square
and sine square of it

00:05:47.260 --> 00:05:50.715
is the reflection
and the transmission

00:05:50.715 --> 00:05:51.590
of the beam splitter.

00:06:00.520 --> 00:06:01.900
Any questions at that point?

00:06:09.430 --> 00:06:15.870
Let me now introduce
matrix representation,

00:06:15.870 --> 00:06:18.040
which will come in handy.

00:06:18.040 --> 00:06:23.370
You remember that you transform
an operator-- the mode

00:06:23.370 --> 00:06:26.360
operator, the annihilation
operator a and b.

00:06:26.360 --> 00:06:33.300
We multiply with the beam
splitter operator on the left

00:06:33.300 --> 00:06:38.150
and on the right,
b dega-- b ab dega.

00:06:38.150 --> 00:06:42.630
But there is often a simpler
way how the right inside

00:06:42.630 --> 00:06:46.850
can be written, and this is by
using a matrix representation,

00:06:46.850 --> 00:06:47.780
which goes as follows.

00:06:54.000 --> 00:07:02.770
We can say that the two
operators are transformed

00:07:02.770 --> 00:07:16.650
by the following
matrix, and this matrix

00:07:16.650 --> 00:07:18.460
represents the beam splitter.

00:07:21.460 --> 00:07:29.790
So that's what the beam splitter
does to the mode operators.

00:07:29.790 --> 00:07:32.170
Now, we want to talk about
what does the beam splitter do

00:07:32.170 --> 00:07:36.220
to quantum states, to
single photon states.

00:07:36.220 --> 00:07:38.630
So now, we want to transform
the single photon states.

00:07:41.990 --> 00:07:43.472
It's a little bit
like, well-- we

00:07:43.472 --> 00:07:45.180
know what to do in
the Heisenberg picture

00:07:45.180 --> 00:07:46.500
to the operator,
but now, we want

00:07:46.500 --> 00:07:48.249
to see what happens
to the wave functions.

00:07:53.060 --> 00:08:00.510
So, now-- I want to
say it very slowly,

00:08:00.510 --> 00:08:07.470
because it shouldn't lead
to any confusion later.

00:08:07.470 --> 00:08:12.720
We have single photons-- we can
have the single photon in mode

00:08:12.720 --> 00:08:15.260
b, or we can have it in mode a.

00:08:15.260 --> 00:08:17.970
These are the two possibilities.

00:08:17.970 --> 00:08:23.025
And right now, I
label it like this--

00:08:23.025 --> 00:08:27.060
where the first number is your
occupation number of mode a,

00:08:27.060 --> 00:08:34.689
and the second number is
your occupation in mode b.

00:08:34.689 --> 00:08:36.230
You have to be a
little bit careful--

00:08:36.230 --> 00:08:39.740
I'm just saying that keep
your alert level high.

00:08:39.740 --> 00:08:46.310
Later, I will use
qubit representation,

00:08:46.310 --> 00:08:50.130
where the qubit one means
the photon is in mode a,

00:08:50.130 --> 00:08:53.640
and the qubit zero means
the photon is in mode b.

00:08:53.640 --> 00:08:57.200
So when we talked about logical
states of our two levels used,

00:08:57.200 --> 00:08:59.640
and the photon can be here
or the photon can be there,

00:08:59.640 --> 00:09:01.740
zero means the photon is there.

00:09:01.740 --> 00:09:04.480
It doesn't mean that
we have zero photons.

00:09:04.480 --> 00:09:06.979
But sometimes, I have to
talk about the photons--

00:09:06.979 --> 00:09:08.520
and that's what I'm
doing right now--

00:09:08.520 --> 00:09:12.410
and zero means no
photon in this mode.

00:09:12.410 --> 00:09:16.280
But I will remind you
of that as we go along.

00:09:16.280 --> 00:09:20.720
So we have the two
quantum states-- one zero,

00:09:20.720 --> 00:09:24.410
and zero one.

00:09:24.410 --> 00:09:27.490
And let's just see what
the beam splitter is

00:09:27.490 --> 00:09:35.450
doing to one photon in mode b.

00:09:40.570 --> 00:09:44.740
I'm changing notation from one
line to the next in my notes.

00:09:50.810 --> 00:09:55.300
Just give me a split second.

00:09:58.606 --> 00:09:59.106
Yes.

00:10:05.351 --> 00:10:06.600
So, let's use this convention.

00:10:11.850 --> 00:10:14.560
So, just to elaborate
what I just said

00:10:14.560 --> 00:10:19.660
is-- this convention one
zero is the direct product

00:10:19.660 --> 00:10:22.480
of the Hilbert space
for mode b, with one

00:10:22.480 --> 00:10:26.800
photon with the Hilbert
space of mode a,

00:10:26.800 --> 00:10:30.710
and we have zero photons there.

00:10:30.710 --> 00:10:33.150
And sometimes, you want
to denote the state

00:10:33.150 --> 00:10:35.040
by putting a comma in between.

00:10:35.040 --> 00:10:36.060
That's all the same.

00:10:39.350 --> 00:10:46.340
So, how do we transform
the quantum state

00:10:46.340 --> 00:10:48.310
with the beam splitter operator?

00:10:48.310 --> 00:10:51.150
Well, we could now apply
to the quantum stage,

00:10:51.150 --> 00:10:54.910
but we just learned how to
apply to operators, so let's

00:10:54.910 --> 00:10:58.530
just use what we
already know, because we

00:10:58.530 --> 00:11:04.070
can write the state like this.

00:11:16.530 --> 00:11:23.120
And now, we want
to insert the unit.

00:11:28.260 --> 00:11:43.420
We want to insert the
unit operator b dega b,

00:11:43.420 --> 00:11:49.950
and now, we can use our
knowledge of the operator.

00:11:49.950 --> 00:11:51.520
We know how this transforms.

00:11:51.520 --> 00:11:53.960
We had this above the
transformation of the operators

00:11:53.960 --> 00:12:04.530
b and b dega, and when we apply
b to nothing-- to no photons,

00:12:04.530 --> 00:12:05.300
we get no photons.

00:12:08.450 --> 00:12:12.310
So now, by taking from the
page above the transformation

00:12:12.310 --> 00:12:16.180
or the operator b dega,
it's a linear combination

00:12:16.180 --> 00:12:19.920
of a dega and b dega.

00:12:19.920 --> 00:12:24.130
We find what we expect--
the photon can now

00:12:24.130 --> 00:12:29.870
be in the same mode, or it
can appear in the other mode.

00:12:33.170 --> 00:12:37.740
And the coefficients from the
transformation of cosine theta

00:12:37.740 --> 00:12:39.310
minus sine theta.

00:12:43.680 --> 00:12:49.830
And if you would send the
other state through the beam

00:12:49.830 --> 00:12:59.930
splitter, we find the cosine
theta sine theta component.

00:13:10.810 --> 00:13:13.670
So, since the total
probability to have a photon

00:13:13.670 --> 00:13:16.800
is cosine square plus
sine square is unity,

00:13:16.800 --> 00:13:20.000
we find what we expected,
but it's nice to see it.

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:31.940
Namely, that b conserves the
photon number-- of course,

00:13:31.940 --> 00:13:34.270
this should have been
obvious from the outset,

00:13:34.270 --> 00:13:37.860
because we used a Hermitian
operator, a unitary time

00:13:37.860 --> 00:13:40.190
evolution, and that
is energy- conserving.

00:13:44.390 --> 00:13:49.440
What happens if we
use a state which

00:13:49.440 --> 00:13:55.180
has one photon in
each mode, and we

00:13:55.180 --> 00:13:58.570
act on it with
the beam splitter?

00:14:04.740 --> 00:14:11.740
Well, it gives a superposition
of the two photons

00:14:11.740 --> 00:14:15.770
can now be in either
of the two modes,

00:14:15.770 --> 00:14:21.150
or they can be distributed
one in each mode.

00:14:21.150 --> 00:14:27.800
And the coefficients are because
we have two transformations,

00:14:27.800 --> 00:14:30.575
products of sine and cosine.

00:14:33.360 --> 00:14:39.630
Here is cosine square
plus sine square theta.

00:14:39.630 --> 00:14:44.390
Here is a plus sine, square
root two plus square root two.

00:14:48.760 --> 00:14:56.040
So that means if we allow one
photon to be in each mode,

00:14:56.040 --> 00:14:59.740
it leads us actually out of the
Hilbert space of single photon

00:14:59.740 --> 00:15:02.190
states, because we have
a certain probability

00:15:02.190 --> 00:15:06.780
now that we have two
photons in each mode.

00:15:06.780 --> 00:15:07.940
So, we don't want that.

00:15:07.940 --> 00:15:12.740
So if you want to deal
with only one photon,

00:15:12.740 --> 00:15:20.990
we should restrict our
attention, our formalism

00:15:20.990 --> 00:15:34.370
to the states which have
nor more than one photon.

00:15:34.370 --> 00:15:37.820
And now, if we act on those
states with beam splitters,

00:15:37.820 --> 00:15:43.740
we don't get out of this
subspace or fill that space.

00:15:43.740 --> 00:15:59.150
However, we also want to
omit this state because it's

00:15:59.150 --> 00:16:02.350
more elegant to do it, but also,
if you have a single photon

00:16:02.350 --> 00:16:06.830
state and we have a detector
which has not 100% efficiency

00:16:06.830 --> 00:16:08.770
and we do a
measurement-- well, we

00:16:08.770 --> 00:16:10.900
don't know if we have
the state zero one,

00:16:10.900 --> 00:16:14.550
but we just didn't detect it,
or we had the state zero zero.

00:16:14.550 --> 00:16:17.410
Whereas if you deal
with two states

00:16:17.410 --> 00:16:25.280
where you always have a
photon-- exactly one photon--

00:16:25.280 --> 00:16:28.610
and you read out your system
and you detect nothing,

00:16:28.610 --> 00:16:31.100
well you discard
the measurement.

00:16:31.100 --> 00:16:35.390
And then, you only
take the measurements

00:16:35.390 --> 00:16:36.940
which have detected one photon.

00:16:36.940 --> 00:16:41.870
So you have the ability to
deal with finite efficiencies

00:16:41.870 --> 00:16:43.890
and losses in a very
straightforward way.

