00:17:24.839 --> 00:17:27.790
Other question?

00:17:27.790 --> 00:17:29.070
Good.

00:17:29.070 --> 00:17:31.700
So what I just said, that we
want to restrict the Hilbert

00:17:31.700 --> 00:17:38.290
space to exactly
one photon, this

00:17:38.290 --> 00:17:43.040
is so important for
implementations and discussions

00:17:43.040 --> 00:17:47.620
of quantum information protocols
that it has its own name.

00:17:47.620 --> 00:17:50.900
It's called the
dual-rail photon state.

00:17:58.480 --> 00:18:01.860
The dual-rail
photon state space.

00:18:01.860 --> 00:18:06.200
Exactly one photon, but the
photon can either be in mode a

00:18:06.200 --> 00:18:09.242
or in mode b.

00:18:09.242 --> 00:18:13.690
So this part-- this dual-rail
photon state space--

00:18:13.690 --> 00:18:30.070
is a Hilbert space which has a
basis which is zero one and one

00:18:30.070 --> 00:18:34.440
zero, and this is of
course a two-level system.

00:18:38.970 --> 00:18:44.410
In this so-defined
Hilbert space,

00:18:44.410 --> 00:18:52.930
we can have an arbitrary
state, [? psi ?] which

00:18:52.930 --> 00:18:56.680
is-- as in any two-dimensional
Hilbert space--

00:18:56.680 --> 00:19:00.320
it's a linear superposition
of your two base

00:19:00.320 --> 00:19:03.140
states with coefficients
alpha and beta.

00:19:10.950 --> 00:19:18.660
And the few of them for which
we have prepared right now

00:19:18.660 --> 00:19:28.050
is that any possible state
of this Hilbert space

00:19:28.050 --> 00:19:36.575
can be created from any
of the base state, that

00:19:36.575 --> 00:19:48.520
is from zero one simply by beam
splitters and phase shifters.

00:19:59.740 --> 00:20:02.810
When I taught this unit the last
time, I went through the proof,

00:20:02.810 --> 00:20:07.650
but I want to make room for more
in-class discussion like we had

00:20:07.650 --> 00:20:09.590
on Wednesday with
the clicker question,

00:20:09.590 --> 00:20:13.140
so what I decided is I give
you the idea behind the proof,

00:20:13.140 --> 00:20:17.160
and the formal parts
you can simply fill in

00:20:17.160 --> 00:20:20.220
by reading about it
on the Wiki page.

00:20:20.220 --> 00:20:23.250
So, let me just
focus on the idea.

00:20:23.250 --> 00:20:29.130
So the proof is that
if I use some column

00:20:29.130 --> 00:20:36.670
vector for alpha beta-- that
we can identify with the beam

00:20:36.670 --> 00:20:38.630
splitter and the
phase shifter-- we

00:20:38.630 --> 00:20:42.780
can identify them as
rotation operators.

00:20:42.780 --> 00:20:50.050
This is immediate obvious if I
use the transformation on psi

00:20:50.050 --> 00:21:00.670
by beam splitter, we learned
just a few minutes ago

00:21:00.670 --> 00:21:03.810
how the beam splitter operator
acts on the base state.

00:21:03.810 --> 00:21:06.790
So now, we know how it
acts on an arbitrary

00:21:06.790 --> 00:21:08.780
linear combination.

00:21:08.780 --> 00:21:13.030
And the matrix here
is nothing else

00:21:13.030 --> 00:21:18.800
than the rotation
matrix with the minus

00:21:18.800 --> 00:21:22.490
sign around the y-axis.

00:21:36.340 --> 00:21:40.220
So that's a beam splitter.

00:21:43.040 --> 00:21:51.110
The phase shifter is
not changing any state.

00:21:51.110 --> 00:22:02.130
It shifts one of the states
by e to the minus i phi,

00:22:02.130 --> 00:22:06.740
but I can sort of summarize
it by taking half of it

00:22:06.740 --> 00:22:12.110
out as a prefector,
and then adding here

00:22:12.110 --> 00:22:14.650
e to the i phi over two.

00:22:17.200 --> 00:22:23.780
And this here is
immediately recognized

00:22:23.780 --> 00:22:26.970
as the rotation matrix
around the z-axis.

00:22:30.480 --> 00:22:33.680
Now, you may ask
what about this?

00:22:33.680 --> 00:22:37.840
Well, this is an irrelevant
global phase factor.

00:22:42.340 --> 00:22:44.406
If you have any state
in Hilbert space

00:22:44.406 --> 00:22:46.650
and you change the global
phase, it doesn't matter.

00:22:51.880 --> 00:22:59.260
Therefore, we are realizing
that the beam splitter

00:22:59.260 --> 00:23:04.910
is a rotation around the y-axis.

00:23:04.910 --> 00:23:07.720
It's now a definitional thing,
but we put a factor of two

00:23:07.720 --> 00:23:16.360
here by an angle two theta,
and the phase shifter

00:23:16.360 --> 00:23:23.131
is a rotation around the
z-axis by an angle phi.

00:23:27.280 --> 00:23:37.370
Now, with that, we
can formulate what

00:23:37.370 --> 00:23:42.390
is called Bloch's theorem,
that any unitary operation

00:23:42.390 --> 00:23:44.310
of a two-dimensional
Hilbert space

00:23:44.310 --> 00:23:47.340
can be written as a
product of rotations.

00:23:47.340 --> 00:23:51.130
Now, let's first count an
arbitrary unitary operation

00:23:51.130 --> 00:23:53.660
while a two by two
matrix in complex space

00:23:53.660 --> 00:23:59.280
has eight numbers-- four real
parts, four imaginary parts.

00:23:59.280 --> 00:24:01.320
But if the matrix
is unitary, they

00:24:01.320 --> 00:24:03.350
are only four
independent elements--

00:24:03.350 --> 00:24:05.970
alpha, beta, gamma, delta.

00:24:05.970 --> 00:24:09.960
And if you parametrize the
unitary matrix with alpha,

00:24:09.960 --> 00:24:13.950
beta, gamma, delta which is
shown in the weekly notes,

00:24:13.950 --> 00:24:20.340
then we can write this
arbitrary unitary matrix

00:24:20.340 --> 00:24:24.620
by a combination of an
overall phase factor.

00:24:27.182 --> 00:24:29.140
Which is irrelevant
because it's a global phase

00:24:29.140 --> 00:24:35.470
factor-- and then a rotation
around z, a rotation around y,

00:24:35.470 --> 00:24:37.665
and a rotation
around the z-axis.

00:24:47.640 --> 00:24:59.380
So, if I rephrase this
theorem in modern language,

00:24:59.380 --> 00:25:05.930
I would say we
have a qubit which

00:25:05.930 --> 00:25:08.790
is a two-level
system characterized

00:25:08.790 --> 00:25:12.620
by two numbers alpha beta.

00:25:12.620 --> 00:25:18.950
And we can do an arbitrary
operation in the Hilbert space

00:25:18.950 --> 00:25:30.780
of the qubit, which is called
an arbitrary single qubit

00:25:30.780 --> 00:25:31.280
operation.

00:25:37.910 --> 00:25:50.250
So, can be performed by phase
shifters and beam splitters.

00:25:57.260 --> 00:26:01.650
Just to make sure that this
doesn't lead to any confusion,

00:26:01.650 --> 00:26:05.430
the phase shift which is
relevant for this Hilbert space

00:26:05.430 --> 00:26:08.310
is a phase shift which is
relative between the two

00:26:08.310 --> 00:26:12.590
states, and can be detected
by an interference experiment.

00:26:12.590 --> 00:26:15.790
Those global phase shifts
cannot be detected.

00:26:15.790 --> 00:26:17.420
There is no observable,
no procedure

00:26:17.420 --> 00:26:23.510
to observe those-- unless you
would have a a third mode.

00:26:23.510 --> 00:26:26.680
But then, we would
expand the Hilbert space

00:26:26.680 --> 00:26:32.240
to three levels and
then, of course,

00:26:32.240 --> 00:26:35.060
it's the global phase shift
in the two-dimension Hilbert

00:26:35.060 --> 00:26:36.622
space becomes a
relative phase shift

00:26:36.622 --> 00:26:38.330
within the three-dimension
Hilbert space.

00:26:42.640 --> 00:26:47.685
And in modern language,
those single qubit operations

00:26:47.685 --> 00:26:50.660
are called quantum gates.

00:26:50.660 --> 00:26:54.980
So, all gates which
act on a single qubit

00:26:54.980 --> 00:27:00.120
can be realized with phase
shifters and beam splitters.

00:27:00.120 --> 00:27:03.870
Let me give you one
example for that.

00:27:03.870 --> 00:27:08.980
In quantum computation,
quantum information science,

00:27:08.980 --> 00:27:14.710
there is a very important
gate-- the Hadamard gate,

00:27:14.710 --> 00:27:19.130
which is described by
a transformation which

00:27:19.130 --> 00:27:23.430
has 1 minus 111.

00:27:23.430 --> 00:27:28.790
And I said it can be realized
with a beam splitter and phase

00:27:28.790 --> 00:27:29.930
shifter.

00:27:29.930 --> 00:27:37.930
So let me just show it to you
in using our symbolic language.

00:27:37.930 --> 00:27:42.430
So if you look at the matrix
we had derived for the beam

00:27:42.430 --> 00:27:48.480
splitter, you realize that
we get the Hadamard gate

00:27:48.480 --> 00:27:50.730
by aiding the phase
shifter by pi.

00:28:02.350 --> 00:28:07.220
So, in that sense, single qubit
operations are checked off.

00:28:07.220 --> 00:28:09.850
We know how to deal with that.

00:28:09.850 --> 00:28:19.780
We want to now move towards
two qubit operations--

00:28:19.780 --> 00:28:22.490
and then, it's getting
really interesting.

00:28:22.490 --> 00:28:26.230
As you may know, you can
do any arbitrary operation

00:28:26.230 --> 00:28:28.650
in many qubits by
just having single

00:28:28.650 --> 00:28:30.700
and two qubit operations.

00:28:30.700 --> 00:28:33.940
Therefore, once we know
how two qubits interact--

00:28:33.940 --> 00:28:38.970
how photons in two
different qubits interact,

00:28:38.970 --> 00:28:43.500
we are done-- we have
universal quantum gates.

00:28:43.500 --> 00:28:46.632
The element I need for
two qubit operation

00:28:46.632 --> 00:28:48.090
is the Mach-Zehnder
interferometer.

00:29:05.770 --> 00:29:11.200
Just a side remark, I introduce
a Mach-Zehnder interferometer

00:29:11.200 --> 00:29:13.760
here as a way to
manipulate qubits.

00:29:13.760 --> 00:29:15.850
On the other hand,
most of you know

00:29:15.850 --> 00:29:19.900
that interferometers for light
and interferometers for atoms

00:29:19.900 --> 00:29:24.120
are used for some of the most
precise measurements ever done.

00:29:24.120 --> 00:29:27.110
So, in that sense,
this shows the dual use

00:29:27.110 --> 00:29:29.340
of the formalism I'm
introducing here.

00:29:29.340 --> 00:29:32.110
We really use some of the
formalism and the language

00:29:32.110 --> 00:29:34.630
we develop here for
qubit operation,

00:29:34.630 --> 00:29:39.350
and discuss next week
the ultimate accuracy--

00:29:39.350 --> 00:29:41.200
the fundamental
limits to the accuracy

00:29:41.200 --> 00:29:43.100
you can get in
precision measurements

00:29:43.100 --> 00:29:44.100
based on interferometry.

00:29:53.995 --> 00:29:55.520
Let me just write
down the sentence

00:29:55.520 --> 00:29:58.080
because it has a lot
of key words in it.

00:29:58.080 --> 00:30:04.390
So the dual-rail photon
presentation of a qubit-- this

00:30:04.390 --> 00:30:05.800
is what we have achieved so far.

00:30:15.940 --> 00:30:20.340
So this allows us now to
discuss interferometers simply

00:30:20.340 --> 00:30:21.268
as [INAUDIBLE] gates.

00:30:41.210 --> 00:30:48.746
And what isn't interferometer--
an interferometer is,

00:30:48.746 --> 00:30:51.870
in its basic [INAUDIBLE],
you have a beam splitter,

00:30:51.870 --> 00:30:54.700
you have two paths, and then
you use another beam splitter

00:30:54.700 --> 00:30:57.167
which recombines the two beams.

00:30:57.167 --> 00:30:58.625
So, let me draw
two beam splitters.

00:31:09.020 --> 00:31:12.300
These are two beam splitters.

00:31:12.300 --> 00:31:20.770
We have an input [INAUDIBLE]
b, an input mode a.

00:31:20.770 --> 00:31:22.030
They are sort of mixed.

00:31:22.030 --> 00:31:25.090
Here are the two arms
of the interferometer.

00:31:25.090 --> 00:31:29.230
And now, we create output
modes b prime and a prime.

00:31:33.070 --> 00:31:38.810
What we have introduced
here is the beam splitter b,

00:31:38.810 --> 00:31:43.880
and by putting the dot on the
other side, this is b dega.

00:31:43.880 --> 00:31:50.320
Since b dega times b equals
one equals the identity,

00:31:50.320 --> 00:31:53.400
this interferometer
is doing nothing.

00:31:53.400 --> 00:31:55.410
If the photon
starts in mode b, it

00:31:55.410 --> 00:31:57.680
comes out in the upper mode b.

00:31:57.680 --> 00:32:01.580
If it starts in a, it
comes out in the mode a.

00:32:01.580 --> 00:32:05.290
But of course, this
is just the beginning,

00:32:05.290 --> 00:32:15.410
because we can now introduce
here an arbitrary phase shift

00:32:15.410 --> 00:32:16.600
phi.

00:32:16.600 --> 00:32:18.470
And now, it is an
interferometer.

00:32:18.470 --> 00:32:21.090
Now, we can read
out with the output

00:32:21.090 --> 00:32:26.450
the phase shift, and ultimately,
with very high precision.

00:32:26.450 --> 00:32:28.570
I what you to appreciate that.

00:32:28.570 --> 00:32:34.280
If we had used single qubits
in one mode-- no photon,

00:32:34.280 --> 00:32:36.390
one photon.

00:32:36.390 --> 00:32:38.680
I gave you many reasons
why we shouldn't do that,

00:32:38.680 --> 00:32:40.700
but then, we would be
dealing with one mode,

00:32:40.700 --> 00:32:42.200
and this would
actually be something

00:32:42.200 --> 00:32:44.570
which involves two qubits.

00:32:44.570 --> 00:32:48.420
But since our
single qubit system

00:32:48.420 --> 00:32:52.580
is a two-level system where
the photon is here and there,

00:32:52.580 --> 00:32:56.800
we can now send single photons
with the interferometer--

00:32:56.800 --> 00:33:02.140
describe the interferometer
as a single qubit operation.

00:33:02.140 --> 00:33:04.810
At least it's nice.

00:33:04.810 --> 00:33:07.142
It allows us to
keep things simple,

00:33:07.142 --> 00:33:09.100
and discuss things at a
very fundamental level.

00:33:14.460 --> 00:33:18.470
So, what we want to
figure out-- what

00:33:18.470 --> 00:33:21.080
is this interferometer doing?

00:33:21.080 --> 00:33:27.390
So, we want to know if we
have an input state-- what

00:33:27.390 --> 00:33:28.950
is the output state?

00:33:28.950 --> 00:33:33.720
And the input state can now
be any arbitrary wave function

00:33:33.720 --> 00:33:35.660
in our dual-rail Hilbert space.

00:33:35.660 --> 00:33:38.420
So, it's always
one photon, but it

00:33:38.420 --> 00:33:43.730
can be in a random
superposition in an arbitrary

00:33:43.730 --> 00:33:47.580
superposition of states a and b.

00:33:47.580 --> 00:33:50.950
Well, with the formalism
we have developed now,

00:33:50.950 --> 00:33:52.720
it becomes very simple.

00:33:52.720 --> 00:33:57.220
All we have to do is we have
to act with the first beam

00:33:57.220 --> 00:34:01.430
splitter with a phase shifter,
and with a second beam splitter

00:34:01.430 --> 00:34:03.740
onto the state.

00:34:03.740 --> 00:34:14.070
And this is nothing else than
taking two rotation matrices

00:34:14.070 --> 00:34:15.600
and multiplying them.

00:34:20.960 --> 00:34:23.659
The beam splitter
we have chosen,

00:34:23.659 --> 00:34:26.170
I said there was sort
of a phase convention

00:34:26.170 --> 00:34:29.445
when I peeked the beam splitter.

00:34:29.445 --> 00:34:33.590
It is a rotation by pi over 2.

00:34:33.590 --> 00:34:38.449
This is minus pi over 2, and
the z-rotation is by minus phi.

00:34:46.010 --> 00:34:51.000
I'm not sure if I manage to do
that, but if this is the y-axis

00:34:51.000 --> 00:34:54.980
and we start with the qubit,
the first beam splitter

00:34:54.980 --> 00:34:57.340
rotates it down.

00:34:57.340 --> 00:35:02.620
Then, the rotation by z-- thus,
that-- and the second beam

00:35:02.620 --> 00:35:05.700
splitter rotates by y.

00:35:05.700 --> 00:35:09.080
Therefore, the
qubit is like that.

00:35:09.080 --> 00:35:15.000
Therefore, if you count
all x's with the things

00:35:15.000 --> 00:35:17.530
I did is-- I started
with a qubit here.

00:35:17.530 --> 00:35:20.170
It went down like
this, like this.

00:35:20.170 --> 00:35:22.000
So what I did is--
in the end, I simply

00:35:22.000 --> 00:35:24.970
rotated it around the x-axis.

00:35:24.970 --> 00:35:27.630
If you want, you can
multiply the matrices,

00:35:27.630 --> 00:35:33.440
or you can draw block
sphere visualization.

00:35:33.440 --> 00:35:41.170
That you say we have an
x-axis, y-axis, and z-axis.

00:35:41.170 --> 00:35:42.330
So the z is vertical.

00:35:46.160 --> 00:35:55.300
So, we started out with
the qubit along the z-axis.

00:35:55.300 --> 00:35:58.110
The first one was rotation
around the y-axis.

00:36:02.300 --> 00:36:03.980
So then, we were here.

00:36:03.980 --> 00:36:15.880
The second operation was
rotation around the z-axis.

00:36:15.880 --> 00:36:26.340
And then, we have to rotate
back around the y-axis, which

00:36:26.340 --> 00:36:30.920
eventually gives this
as the final state.

00:36:30.920 --> 00:36:33.610
So ultimately, the
product of all this

00:36:33.610 --> 00:36:37.225
is a rotation around the x-axis.

00:36:41.650 --> 00:36:44.354
Our interferometer--
I'm not sure

00:36:44.354 --> 00:36:45.770
if you've ever
heard the language,

00:36:45.770 --> 00:36:47.840
but it's really
elegant and powerful.

00:36:47.840 --> 00:36:52.330
An interferometer with
an arbitrary phase

00:36:52.330 --> 00:36:55.350
in this two-level Hilbert
space with this sort

00:36:55.350 --> 00:36:58.430
of geometric interpretation
we have given,

00:36:58.430 --> 00:37:01.765
is nothing else than a
rotation around the x-axis.

00:37:08.450 --> 00:37:15.250
Therefore, we know immediately
the two limiting cases when

00:37:15.250 --> 00:37:21.100
we rotate by zero,
it's sort of balanced.

00:37:21.100 --> 00:37:23.450
Output and input are the
same, because we're not

00:37:23.450 --> 00:37:26.520
rotating at all.

00:37:26.520 --> 00:37:30.460
Whereas if we have a phase
shift of 180 degrees,

00:37:30.460 --> 00:37:33.590
we swap the two qubits.

00:37:33.590 --> 00:37:40.840
So, we swap the two
modes, and swapping modes

00:37:40.840 --> 00:37:43.550
is an inversion of the qubit.

00:37:53.430 --> 00:38:00.390
So that's almost trivial,
but we need this definition--

00:38:00.390 --> 00:38:03.490
we need this knowledge to
take it to the next step.

00:38:03.490 --> 00:38:05.160
Remember, we want
to do something

00:38:05.160 --> 00:38:07.870
more interesting than
rotating two level systems.

00:38:07.870 --> 00:38:12.420
We want to get two qubits,
combine them, entangle them,

00:38:12.420 --> 00:38:13.770
and all that.

00:38:13.770 --> 00:38:19.200
So what we need for
that is-- we have

00:38:19.200 --> 00:38:21.660
to expand the Hilbert space.

00:38:21.660 --> 00:38:25.150
I introduced the Mach-Zehnder
interferometer as the device

00:38:25.150 --> 00:38:26.400
to do it.

00:38:26.400 --> 00:38:30.000
But now, we need a way
how a second photon

00:38:30.000 --> 00:38:33.410
from another qubit can
interact with the photon

00:38:33.410 --> 00:38:35.420
of our first qubit.

00:38:35.420 --> 00:38:39.020
And we want to do that
by introducing first

00:38:39.020 --> 00:38:41.440
the non-linear Mach-Zehnder
interferometer.

00:38:41.440 --> 00:38:44.810
I want to throw in a
non-linear element,

00:38:44.810 --> 00:38:48.640
and then we are ready to
allow the second qubit

00:38:48.640 --> 00:38:53.430
through the non-linear element
to manipulate the first qubit.

00:38:53.430 --> 00:38:55.960
And then, we have
interactions between qubit.

00:38:55.960 --> 00:38:57.580
We have two qubit gates.

00:39:17.450 --> 00:39:21.202
Let me maybe just
deviate for my notes.

00:39:21.202 --> 00:39:22.910
I really want to show
you what I'm doing,

00:39:22.910 --> 00:39:26.510
and that you have it clearly
in mind where I'm aiming it.

00:39:26.510 --> 00:39:31.160
So what we want to accomplish
is-- instead of having a phase

00:39:31.160 --> 00:39:34.080
shifter with an externally
controlled phase,

00:39:34.080 --> 00:39:38.480
I want to put in some
non-linear crystal-- which

00:39:38.480 --> 00:39:41.820
has an index of refraction
which has a phase shift.

00:39:41.820 --> 00:39:45.070
But now, the face that
the non-linear crystal

00:39:45.070 --> 00:39:47.780
has the property, that
its index of refraction

00:39:47.780 --> 00:39:54.740
changes when I take another
laser beam and send it through.

00:39:54.740 --> 00:39:57.530
So, the laser beam through--
because the index of refraction

00:39:57.530 --> 00:40:01.400
is intensity-dependent,
the green laser beam

00:40:01.400 --> 00:40:06.420
changes index of refraction of
the non-linear crystal-- also

00:40:06.420 --> 00:40:08.340
called Kerr medium.

00:40:08.340 --> 00:40:11.240
And that means now,
because the blue beam

00:40:11.240 --> 00:40:15.060
goes through the same crystal,
that the green beam controls

00:40:15.060 --> 00:40:18.520
now the phase shift
of the blue beam.

00:40:18.520 --> 00:40:23.302
And now, we have interacting
photons-- one photon interacts

00:40:23.302 --> 00:40:24.260
with the second photon.

00:40:28.340 --> 00:40:29.120
Let's work it out.

00:40:32.160 --> 00:40:37.940
So our goal is to
develop a description

00:40:37.940 --> 00:40:40.620
for non-linear Mach-Zehnder
interferometer.

00:40:50.330 --> 00:40:53.080
What we need is a
non-linear medium.

00:40:53.080 --> 00:40:56.140
So, let me just introduce
for two or three minutes

00:40:56.140 --> 00:40:58.289
non-linear medium,
how we describe it,

00:40:58.289 --> 00:41:00.080
and then we put in into
our interferometer.

00:41:03.840 --> 00:41:08.060
So, in linear optics--
just to remind you,

00:41:08.060 --> 00:41:12.940
we have a polarization on
electric dipole moment, which

00:41:12.940 --> 00:41:17.420
is proportional to the
electric field of light,

00:41:17.420 --> 00:41:20.840
and x i is the polarizability.

00:41:20.840 --> 00:41:24.030
The most complicated case, it
can be polarizability tensor.

00:41:32.930 --> 00:41:35.110
Now, this is linear.

00:41:35.110 --> 00:41:42.720
If you want two non-linear, then
we have the linear relationship

00:41:42.720 --> 00:41:46.890
simply as you can say the first
terminal [INAUDIBLE] expansion.

00:41:46.890 --> 00:41:50.900
So we expand the response
of the medium in powers

00:41:50.900 --> 00:41:57.480
of the electric field, and
we have the susceptibilities

00:41:57.480 --> 00:42:02.400
chi 1, chi 2, chi 3, and so on.

00:42:07.670 --> 00:42:13.230
We have already encountered
a non-linear element which

00:42:13.230 --> 00:42:19.610
had a chi 2 susceptibility,
and these where the crystals

00:42:19.610 --> 00:42:29.400
we put in our OPOs into our
optical parametric oscillators.

00:42:29.400 --> 00:42:32.290
Remember, the optical
parametric oscillator

00:42:32.290 --> 00:42:36.770
involved-- how many modes?

00:42:36.770 --> 00:42:38.730
Three.

00:42:38.730 --> 00:42:43.890
We had one photon, which was
broken down into two photons.

00:42:43.890 --> 00:42:46.350
But that also means
that the reverse process

00:42:46.350 --> 00:42:51.460
is you drive the beam-- you
drive the OPO with omega,

00:42:51.460 --> 00:42:56.730
but the e square term creates
an electric polarization

00:42:56.730 --> 00:42:57.800
as 2 omega.

00:42:57.800 --> 00:43:00.680
And if you have an oscillating
polarization as 2 omega,

00:43:00.680 --> 00:43:02.720
you create light at 2 omega.

00:43:02.720 --> 00:43:06.020
So, I just want to remind you
that the chi square term is

00:43:06.020 --> 00:43:08.779
what we have
already encountered.

00:43:08.779 --> 00:43:11.070
That's not what we need for
the non-linear Mach-Zehnder

00:43:11.070 --> 00:43:12.620
interferometer.

00:43:12.620 --> 00:43:17.100
What we need now is
a chi 3 interaction,

00:43:17.100 --> 00:43:18.485
which is the Kerr medium.

00:43:22.790 --> 00:43:26.820
Because we want to realize
the following Hamiltonian.

00:43:31.000 --> 00:43:34.410
The Hamiltonian, the Kerr
medium is also called cross--

00:43:34.410 --> 00:43:37.460
that's cx --
cross-phase modulation.

00:43:37.460 --> 00:43:40.795
One beam can affect the
phase of another beam,

00:43:40.795 --> 00:43:42.545
and this is called
cross-phase modulation.

00:43:45.190 --> 00:43:47.300
There's also
self-phase modulation--

00:43:47.300 --> 00:43:49.540
that one laser beam changes
the index of refraction

00:43:49.540 --> 00:43:52.655
for itself-- but here, we want
the cross-phase modulation.

00:43:56.710 --> 00:44:07.130
So, we know that if we have a
mode, and we shift its phase,

00:44:07.130 --> 00:44:09.850
we're not changing any photons.

00:44:09.850 --> 00:44:12.420
So if we're in an
eigenstate of mode a

00:44:12.420 --> 00:44:17.260
with one, two, or three photons
and we simply shift its phase,

00:44:17.260 --> 00:44:21.870
we are diagonal in a dega
a, and the phase shift

00:44:21.870 --> 00:44:24.170
is proportional
to prefector here.

00:44:24.170 --> 00:44:28.115
So this Hamiltonian is simply a
phase shift for photons in mode

00:44:28.115 --> 00:44:35.170
a, but if you now multiply
that with b dega b,

00:44:35.170 --> 00:44:38.680
the phase shift is now
proportional to the number

00:44:38.680 --> 00:44:40.900
of photons in mode b.

00:44:40.900 --> 00:44:43.830
Now, we have a situation that
the phase shift from mode

00:44:43.830 --> 00:44:48.440
a proportional to the intensity
in beam b, and vice versa.

00:44:48.440 --> 00:44:51.140
So, I think it's self-evident
that this Hamiltonian is

00:44:51.140 --> 00:44:53.930
sequential description
of the process we

00:44:53.930 --> 00:44:55.080
want to introduce know.

00:45:02.760 --> 00:45:05.300
This is the cross-phase
modulation Hamiltonian.

00:45:11.010 --> 00:45:14.400
Isn't it much more elegant
to describe non-linear optics

00:45:14.400 --> 00:45:18.150
with Hamiltonians than with
parametrized susceptibilities

00:45:18.150 --> 00:45:18.994
and all that?

00:45:18.994 --> 00:45:20.910
It's just amazing-- you
write in a few letters

00:45:20.910 --> 00:45:24.390
and it has all the power of
the classical description--

00:45:24.390 --> 00:45:27.060
plus extra, because it
includes quantum fluctuations

00:45:27.060 --> 00:45:29.380
and everything.

00:45:29.380 --> 00:45:31.780
I hope you appreciate
the power of the language

00:45:31.780 --> 00:45:33.460
we are developing.

00:45:33.460 --> 00:45:35.420
This is the cross-phase
modulation Hamiltonian.

00:45:39.350 --> 00:45:45.320
And now, we want to
use this Hamiltonian

00:45:45.320 --> 00:45:55.365
in a crystal of
lengths L Well, you

00:45:55.365 --> 00:46:02.230
