01:05:32.990 --> 01:05:37.050
What I want to rather do is-- I
want to continue our discussion

01:05:37.050 --> 01:05:41.440
and now talk about the object
we have encountered here--

01:05:41.440 --> 01:05:42.625
namely, entangled states.

01:05:45.140 --> 01:05:48.650
But if you have any
questions, if you

01:05:48.650 --> 01:05:52.100
want me to explain anything
more about the single qubit

01:05:52.100 --> 01:05:55.150
manipulation, the
dual-rail photon state,

01:05:55.150 --> 01:05:56.784
I would be happy to do that.

01:06:18.280 --> 01:06:51.630
Our next chapter is
on entangled photons,

01:06:51.630 --> 01:06:57.050
and what we can accomplish
in the next 10 or 15 minutes

01:06:57.050 --> 01:07:00.585
is mainly a definition and
some of the properties.

01:07:04.970 --> 01:07:07.830
What we will do
next week is we will

01:07:07.830 --> 01:07:11.617
talk about how we measure
entanglement-- you already

01:07:11.617 --> 01:07:14.460
had one homework assignment
where you discussed one

01:07:14.460 --> 01:07:16.690
way to measure
entanglement, but there

01:07:16.690 --> 01:07:18.890
are others which we want
to discuss next week.

01:07:21.810 --> 01:07:27.260
I also want to show you next
week how entanglement leads

01:07:27.260 --> 01:07:30.830
to the Einstein-Podolsky-Rosen
paradox and Bell's

01:07:30.830 --> 01:07:32.470
inequalities.

01:07:32.470 --> 01:07:34.310
And eventually, I
want to show you

01:07:34.310 --> 01:07:39.520
how you can entangle
not only photons,

01:07:39.520 --> 01:07:42.040
but how you can entangle atoms.

01:07:42.040 --> 01:07:43.610
But that's an outlook.

01:07:43.610 --> 01:07:46.340
I think, first of all,
we want to understand

01:07:46.340 --> 01:07:47.260
what is entanglement.

01:07:50.780 --> 01:07:59.740
Entanglement is-- let me
first [? motivate ?] it.

01:07:59.740 --> 01:08:05.850
Many people regard entanglement
as the most quantum

01:08:05.850 --> 01:08:07.700
essence you can find.

01:08:12.080 --> 01:08:13.620
Well, there's
always a discussion,

01:08:13.620 --> 01:08:16.510
but it's really quantum.

01:08:16.510 --> 01:08:19.760
Some people would say
waves are quantum.

01:08:19.760 --> 01:08:23.774
But often, we find
quantum systems--

01:08:23.774 --> 01:08:26.720
very famously, Bose-Einstein
condensates, which really

01:08:26.720 --> 01:08:29.380
behave like
electromagnetic waves.

01:08:29.380 --> 01:08:30.410
They can be split.

01:08:30.410 --> 01:08:31.880
They can interfere.

01:08:31.880 --> 01:08:35.960
But Bose-Einstein condensates
are so big, have so many atoms

01:08:35.960 --> 01:08:39.859
that you hardly ever encounter
quantum fluctuations.

01:08:39.859 --> 01:08:42.790
You're really in the classical
limit of matter waves,

01:08:42.790 --> 01:08:47.370
and I would actually
say this is maybe not

01:08:47.370 --> 01:08:48.899
at the heart of
quantum mechanics.

01:08:48.899 --> 01:08:50.520
While it's nice,
it's powerful, it's

01:08:50.520 --> 01:08:54.540
important-- but this is not
really the new feature which

01:08:54.540 --> 01:08:58.540
quantum mechanics has
shown us in nature.

01:08:58.540 --> 01:09:01.010
You would say-- well,
what else is quantum?

01:09:01.010 --> 01:09:02.810
Maybe certain
quantum fluctuations

01:09:02.810 --> 01:09:05.040
going down to single
photons, and I

01:09:05.040 --> 01:09:06.952
would agree that's
a quantization

01:09:06.952 --> 01:09:08.160
of the electromagnetic field.

01:09:08.160 --> 01:09:11.290
That's much more quantum than
having millions of condensates,

01:09:11.290 --> 01:09:15.330
millions of condensed
atoms in one single wave.

01:09:15.330 --> 01:09:17.899
But what I would say
is even more quantum

01:09:17.899 --> 01:09:20.950
than the single photon
is the entanglement.

01:09:20.950 --> 01:09:25.420
Entanglement is sort of
pure quantum mechanics.

01:09:25.420 --> 01:09:28.300
With single photons, you
can still use intuition.

01:09:28.300 --> 01:09:32.689
But with entanglement,
that is really bizarre.

01:09:32.689 --> 01:09:35.985
This is really- I
hate the word, but let

01:09:35.985 --> 01:09:39.569
me use it-- this is sort
of pure quantum weirdness.

01:09:39.569 --> 01:09:43.359
And there are people who have
spent most of their career

01:09:43.359 --> 01:09:47.510
until now to just show the
weirdness of quantum mechanics,

01:09:47.510 --> 01:09:52.779
and showing to what peculiar
phenomena entanglement leads.

01:09:52.779 --> 01:09:57.709
So entanglement has really
lead to a lot of-- I

01:09:57.709 --> 01:10:00.000
should be careful with the
word surprising-- surprising

01:10:00.000 --> 01:10:02.060
always means you didn't
have enough imagination

01:10:02.060 --> 01:10:05.370
to think about it, but yes,
I would say-- really truly

01:10:05.370 --> 01:10:09.330
unanticipated, and in that
sense, surprising developments.

01:10:15.030 --> 01:10:18.610
Entanglement is, therefore,
for me, the most quantum

01:10:18.610 --> 01:10:20.085
aspect of quantum mechanics.

01:10:23.540 --> 01:10:32.590
It was through the
Einstein-Podolsky-Rosen

01:10:32.590 --> 01:10:38.800
argument-- it was actually
Einstein-Podolsky-Rosen

01:10:38.800 --> 01:10:42.890
in the '30s who argued--
Einstein-Podolsky-Rosen were

01:10:42.890 --> 01:10:45.237
really the first--
this was almost 5

01:10:45.237 --> 01:10:47.070
or 10 years after the
development of quantum

01:10:47.070 --> 01:10:47.890
mechanics.

01:10:47.890 --> 01:10:50.600
But it was
Einstein-Podolsky-Rosen

01:10:50.600 --> 01:10:56.185
who looked at the properties
of entangled states.

01:11:01.420 --> 01:11:04.220
This famous experiment
where you have something

01:11:04.220 --> 01:11:06.170
entangled in position
and momentum space.

01:11:06.170 --> 01:11:08.040
And then,
Einstein-Podolsky-Rosen

01:11:08.040 --> 01:11:11.760
found a paradox,
and their conclusion

01:11:11.760 --> 01:11:16.250
was that the properties
of entangled states

01:11:16.250 --> 01:11:19.560
implies that quantum
mechanic is not

01:11:19.560 --> 01:11:23.390
compete-- is not a complete
description of the word.

01:11:26.140 --> 01:11:32.260
Well, we don't any longer
share this opinion.

01:11:32.260 --> 01:11:40.820
It was John Bell and others who
said that entanglement really

01:11:40.820 --> 01:11:54.460
exemplifies that quantum
mechanical correlations go

01:11:54.460 --> 01:12:02.180
beyond classical mechanics--
go beyond the classic picture.

01:12:04.780 --> 01:12:07.370
Therefore, you can say
if you have a quantum

01:12:07.370 --> 01:12:10.600
system like a
Bose-Einstein condensate,

01:12:10.600 --> 01:12:14.130
where you have end
particles doing

01:12:14.130 --> 01:12:16.470
in unison what
one particle does.

01:12:16.470 --> 01:12:19.100
This is sort of like the
laser where many photons do

01:12:19.100 --> 01:12:21.640
what one photon does--
but it fits very, very

01:12:21.640 --> 01:12:25.310
well into the concept of
classical probabilities

01:12:25.310 --> 01:12:28.800
and an intuitive understanding
of why many particles do

01:12:28.800 --> 01:12:30.680
what one particle does.

01:12:30.680 --> 01:12:32.980
But if the particles
are entangled,

01:12:32.980 --> 01:12:36.280
that's almost like you
turbo-charge your system.

01:12:36.280 --> 01:12:39.960
Your system has now more
oomph, more power in it.

01:12:39.960 --> 01:12:43.380
And this is shown that it
has extra correlation-- there

01:12:43.380 --> 01:12:45.785
is something extra in
it, which you would never

01:12:45.785 --> 01:12:48.090
get from any classical limit.

01:12:48.090 --> 01:12:52.340
And this extra oomph,
this extra power

01:12:52.340 --> 01:12:55.600
turns out to be a real resource.

01:12:55.600 --> 01:13:02.490
So, entanglement-- this extra
correlation-- is a resource.

01:13:02.490 --> 01:13:06.270
And resource means it's
good for something.

01:13:06.270 --> 01:13:07.453
It enables teleportation.

01:13:14.340 --> 01:13:19.470
Remember when we talked about
the teleportation scheme--

01:13:19.470 --> 01:13:22.920
Alice and Bob could only
teleport a quantum state

01:13:22.920 --> 01:13:27.240
because they shared
entangled photons.

01:13:27.240 --> 01:13:32.020
It was this entangled state
which Alice manipulated

01:13:32.020 --> 01:13:34.620
with a measurement,
and Bob used this half

01:13:34.620 --> 01:13:37.740
of the entangled state to
recreate the original state.

01:13:37.740 --> 01:13:44.320
So, it's the engine
[INAUDIBLE] up

01:13:44.320 --> 01:13:51.380
behind teleportation in the
world of quantum computation.

01:13:51.380 --> 01:13:55.860
The exponential speedup
of quantum computers

01:13:55.860 --> 01:14:05.400
versus classical computers
in quantum algorithms

01:14:05.400 --> 01:14:07.840
is due to the
entanglement, which

01:14:07.840 --> 01:14:11.430
we can put into
a quantum system.

01:14:11.430 --> 01:14:13.840
And eventually,
next week, you will

01:14:13.840 --> 01:14:17.540
see that if you have
an atom interferometer

01:14:17.540 --> 01:14:28.520
with entangled states,
we can operate it

01:14:28.520 --> 01:14:32.900
at a precision which is
better than short noise.

01:14:36.320 --> 01:14:41.480
So in other words, you use laser
light to measure something,

01:14:41.480 --> 01:14:43.990
and you're limited by
the fundamental noise

01:14:43.990 --> 01:14:45.650
limit of classical physics.

01:14:45.650 --> 01:14:48.630
Now, you entangle
your laser beam

01:14:48.630 --> 01:14:50.380
and you get higher
precision out of it.

01:14:50.380 --> 01:14:53.790
So this shows that entanglement
is a very special resource.

01:14:53.790 --> 01:14:56.070
It's very precious,
very powerful

01:14:56.070 --> 01:14:58.240
and can extend what
physics can do.

01:15:08.630 --> 01:15:09.770
So, let's define it.

01:15:25.960 --> 01:15:27.880
I'm not describing
to you entanglement

01:15:27.880 --> 01:15:29.860
in the most generous situation.

01:15:29.860 --> 01:15:32.880
If you talk about
many modes-- if you

01:15:32.880 --> 01:15:36.570
talk about not just pure states,
but statistical operators--

01:15:36.570 --> 01:15:39.580
it can become quite involved.

01:15:39.580 --> 01:15:43.060
I'd rather start with the
simple situation, which

01:15:43.060 --> 01:15:47.370
for conceptual discussions is
also the most important one.

01:15:47.370 --> 01:15:52.840
I restrict our focus
now on two modes.

01:16:05.530 --> 01:16:13.260
I want to ask if you have two
modes a-- actually, two modes

01:16:13.260 --> 01:16:15.350
means two subsystems here.

01:16:15.350 --> 01:16:20.630
If you have two
subsystems a and b--

01:16:20.630 --> 01:16:23.530
let me tell you what
entanglement is not,

01:16:23.530 --> 01:16:26.220
and then I make
it the definition.

01:16:26.220 --> 01:16:28.100
There wouldn't be
anything special

01:16:28.100 --> 01:16:34.200
if you have a system which
has two parts a and b.

01:16:34.200 --> 01:16:37.100
The global system is psi ab.

01:16:37.100 --> 01:16:40.610
But if your system
would simply factorize

01:16:40.610 --> 01:16:44.750
into a wave function
of subsystem a,

01:16:44.750 --> 01:16:50.270
direct product with
subsystem b, and this here

01:16:50.270 --> 01:16:51.305
is the tensor product.

01:16:54.720 --> 01:16:56.780
Then, there would be
nothing special going on

01:16:56.780 --> 01:16:59.697
between subsystem
a and subsystem b--

01:16:59.697 --> 01:17:00.780
and this is non-entangled.

01:17:03.660 --> 01:17:05.455
Everything else is entangled.

01:17:05.455 --> 01:17:06.580
So, this is our definition.

01:17:10.800 --> 01:17:16.740
When we have two
separate systems a and b,

01:17:16.740 --> 01:17:21.840
we call this situation the
total system bipartite.

01:17:21.840 --> 01:17:27.220
So, a bipartite state which has
sort of half of it in system a,

01:17:27.220 --> 01:17:28.700
half of it in system b.

01:17:39.720 --> 01:17:42.320
We need those two
different systems--

01:17:42.320 --> 01:17:49.230
it's a composite
system a plus b.

01:17:49.230 --> 01:18:13.140
And this state is entangled-- if
and only if you cannot find two

01:18:13.140 --> 01:18:25.496
states psi a and psi b,
such that the state can be

01:18:25.496 --> 01:18:25.995
factorized.

01:18:34.770 --> 01:18:37.950
We need a few examples
to fully comprehend

01:18:37.950 --> 01:18:43.030
this discussion-- what
systems a and b qualify.

01:18:43.030 --> 01:18:46.940
What does it mean if there
does not exist any combination?

01:18:46.940 --> 01:18:48.820
So, let me give you
some examples now,

01:18:48.820 --> 01:18:50.060
and then I think we stop.

01:18:55.170 --> 01:19:02.750
If you have the 0, 0
state, photons in two mode,

01:19:02.750 --> 01:19:09.360
we can factorize it-- and
this is not entangled.

01:19:13.950 --> 01:19:23.600
If you have a state which
is 0, 0 plus 1, 1-- well,

01:19:23.600 --> 01:19:27.020
you cannot write it as a product
of one state times another

01:19:27.020 --> 01:19:27.570
state.

01:19:27.570 --> 01:19:28.319
This is entangled.

01:19:34.530 --> 01:19:51.290
Well, if you take the following
state-- Is that entangled

01:19:51.290 --> 01:19:53.330
or not?

01:19:53.330 --> 01:19:57.970
I've written it as a
sum of four states,

01:19:57.970 --> 01:20:01.520
but if you just stare at
it for a split second,

01:20:01.520 --> 01:20:05.590
you realize you can just write
it as a product of two states.

01:20:05.590 --> 01:20:11.430
It's just a product
of 0, 1 with 0, 1.

01:20:11.430 --> 01:20:14.160
So, a state is not entangled
if you can write it

01:20:14.160 --> 01:20:17.470
as a linear superposition
of those states.

01:20:17.470 --> 01:20:20.140
The definition of
entanglement is--

01:20:20.140 --> 01:20:22.220
if you try hard
and hard and hard,

01:20:22.220 --> 01:20:25.726
and there doesn't exist any
product state decomposition,

01:20:25.726 --> 01:20:26.600
then it is entangled.

01:20:30.200 --> 01:20:31.045
So, that was easy.

01:20:34.000 --> 01:20:38.330
If you use a state like-- let
me just leave the 1, 1 out.

01:20:46.550 --> 01:20:47.530
What about this one?

01:20:55.520 --> 01:21:01.700
Well, you can try as
hard as you want--

01:21:01.700 --> 01:21:04.560
you will not find
the decomposition.

01:21:04.560 --> 01:21:07.350
So eventually,
when I say you have

01:21:07.350 --> 01:21:09.230
to try hard to
find decomposition,

01:21:09.230 --> 01:21:11.440
maybe what we want
is we want to apply

01:21:11.440 --> 01:21:13.970
some operator or some
procedure to this state,

01:21:13.970 --> 01:21:15.870
and get the answer, yes-no.

01:21:15.870 --> 01:21:18.795
This naturally asks for
question-- how in general can

01:21:18.795 --> 01:21:21.000
we measure if a state
is entangled or not?

01:21:21.000 --> 01:21:23.920
But this is something
we'll discuss next week.

01:21:23.920 --> 01:21:27.700
So let me just conclude
with the following.

01:21:27.700 --> 01:21:33.060
I'm focusing here and for pretty
much all of this cause when

01:21:33.060 --> 01:21:35.195
we talk about entanglement,
about pure states.

01:21:39.180 --> 01:21:45.900
If you have decoherence--
if you have the transition

01:21:45.900 --> 01:21:48.890
from pure states to
density matrices--

01:21:48.890 --> 01:21:52.040
it gets much more involved
to talk about entanglement

01:21:52.040 --> 01:21:53.740
and measure entanglement.

01:21:53.740 --> 01:21:56.800
But at least the
basic definition

01:21:56.800 --> 01:22:00.040
can still be maintained
for statistical operators.

01:22:00.040 --> 01:22:02.920
If you describe the system--
the total system by one

01:22:02.920 --> 01:22:07.730
statistical operator-- the
system is not entangled.

01:22:07.730 --> 01:22:10.600
If the statistical
operator can be broken up

01:22:10.600 --> 01:22:14.160
into a direct tensor product
of statistical operator

01:22:14.160 --> 01:22:16.260
for system a and system b.

01:22:16.260 --> 01:22:18.690
Otherwise, the
system is entangled.

01:22:18.690 --> 01:22:21.960
So the basic definition
can be generalized

01:22:21.960 --> 01:22:25.470
to density matrices,
but a lot of things

01:22:25.470 --> 01:22:28.410
become much, much more messy
if you don't have pure states.

01:22:32.420 --> 01:22:35.460
Any last-minute questions?

01:22:35.460 --> 01:22:37.900
See you on Monday.

